	abstract = {The aim of this work was to study the influence of various carbon sources (acetate, glucose, succinate) and nitrate concentration on dissimilatory nitrate reduction rates (denitrification and dissimilatory nitrate reduction to ammonium: DNRA). Without nitrate ammendement the rate ratio DNRA/denitrification was about 11. When the nitrate added was lower than 0.05 mM, the ratio increased 3.8‐fold showing that nitrate ammonifiers have high affinity for nitrate. When nitrate concentration increased up to 0.5 mM, denitrification was stimulated. When glucose, acetate or succinate were added as electron donor, denitrification rates followed the order succinate {\textbackslash}textgreater acetate {\textbackslash}textgreater glucose {\textbackslash}textgreater control, whereas the order of DNRA values was glucose {\textbackslash}textgreater succinate {\textbackslash}textgreater acetate = control. Thus, the DNRA‐to‐denitrification activity ratio is affected by the quantity of carbon and nitrate but also by the theoretical energy of the substrate.},
